div.p:
He applied to numerous intimate acquaintances,
 but found that, though they admired his style of living, and relished the dinners he had given-thought him a good fellow at concerts and soirees-if they were to be believed, their embarrassments were equal to his; and none could help him to a dollar. He realized the "popular creed," 



"If a man is down, give him a thrust; 

Trample the beggar into the dust; 

Presumptuous poverty's quite appalling; 

Knock him over, kick him for falling."

This is a small affair at best, some one may say, but do not 



"Large streams from little fountains flow; 

Tall oaks from little acorns grow!"
